x4freetext: 180Hf Energy Levels Deduced from Thermal and Average
Resonance Neutron-capture Gamma-ray spectra.
In-pile facility at the Argonne CP-5 research
reactor.
Reactor core with a thermal neutron flux
~3.5E+13 n/(cm2.s) at the sample position.
Reactor spectrum.
Probable uncertainties in gamma-ray energies
based on:
. counting statistics,
. complexity of the spectrum,
. calibration of precision screw used to measure Bragg
angle.
Does not include any error in value assumed for K-L
x-rays and measurement of their diffraction angles,
since the combined uncertainty of the primary
calibration (1 part in 40000) is much smaller than
the error quoted for most of the gamma rays.

x4code.headerHelp: Error in value of quantity, defined under ERR-ANALYS

x4freetext: Probable uncertainties of line intensities
due to errors in:
. counting statistics,
. efficiency calibration,
. complexity of the x-ray spectrum,
. uncertainty in the background.
Does not include uncertainty in the relative isotopic
abundance, in the neutron-capture cross section
(~20%) and uncertainties from contribution of
captured resonance neutrons, estimated to 5% of
thermal capture rate.
Unique spin assignments made for 21 levels.
Two K =0 and one K=2 excited state bands identified.
Data taken from Table II of reference.

x4freetext: Three samples used:
1) 324 mg of HfO2 powder enriched to 83.6% in Hf179,
packed in a cavity in a Mg(85%)Al(15%) alloy holder.
2) Natural Hf (13.78% 179Hf) sample.
3) Hf sample enriched to 93.6% in Hf177 (1.1% 179Hf).
7.7-m Argonne bent-crystal spectrometer with a
2-mm thick quartz crystal (310 diffraction planes).
Line width (FWHM) 60 eV at 100 keV and 6.0 keV at
1 MeV. Bank of NaI crystals used to detect the gamma-
ray spectrum as a function of Bragg angle of
spectrometer.
Gamma ray energies normalized so that they agree in
energy and intensity with the GeLi values at the
1065.77 keV doublet.
Data taken from Table II of reference.
